data.create-manually#Create Manually: Nextra works like a Next.js plugin, and it accepts a theme config (layout) to render the page. To start: Install Next.js, Nextra and React npm i react react-dom next nextra yarn add react react-dom next nextra pnpm i react react-dom next nextra Install the docs theme npm i nextra-theme-docs yarn add nextra-theme-docs pnpm i nextra-theme-docs Create the following Next.js config and theme config under the root directory: const withNextra = require('nextra')({ theme: 'nextra-theme-blog', themeConfig: './theme.config.js' // optional: add `staticImage: true` to enable Nextra's auto image import }) module.exports = withNextra() Create a theme.config.js file for the docs theme: /** * @type {import('nextra-theme-docs').DocsThemeConfig} */ export default { project:{ link: 'https://github.com/shuding/nextra' // GitHub link in the navbar }, docsRepositoryBase: 'https://github.com/shuding/nextra/blob/master', // base URL for the docs repository getNextSeoProps: () => ({ titleTemplate: '%s – Nextra' }), navigation: true, darkMode: true, footer: { text: `MIT ${new Date().getFullYear()} © Shu Ding.` }, editLink: { text: 'Edit this page on GitHub' }, logo: ( <> Next.js Static Site Generator ), head: ( <> ), primaryHue: { dark: 204, light: 212 } } More configuration options for the docs theme can be found here. You are good to go! Run yarn next to start. Any .md or .mdx file will turn into a doc page and be displayed in sidebar. You can also create a meta.json file to customize the page order and title. Check the source code: https://github.com/shuding/nextra for more information. You can also use
